<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-545-624  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 545 624.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  August 14 1989 v10 n32 p4(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Air Force SI lags behind. (systems integration)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Millison, Doug.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Two large US Air Force systems-integration projects have fallenway behind schedule, affecting the ability to track wanderingmilitary satellites and to detect surprise enemy attacks.andP;  TheGeneral Accounting Office (GAO) reported that the Air Force'ssecret satellite-control facility uses outdated computers andsoftware.andP;  The IBM systems-integration work is five years behindschedule and millions of dollars over budget.andP;  Criticism has alsobeen directed at problems in updating the computer network atCheyenne Mountain, which houses the country's initial warningsystem for air attacks.andP;  IBM's federal systems division would notcomment on the GAO report.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Integrated SystemsUpgradingMilitaryObsolescenceUnited States. Air Force.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>